    </div></td><td width="32">Â </td></tr><tr><td valign="top"><div class="es-jasper-simpleCalendar" baseurl="/lkml/"></div><div class="threadlist">Messages in this thread</div><ul class="threadlist"><li class="root"><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/102">First message in thread</a></li><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/102">Anton Altaparmakov</a><ul><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/106">Anton Altaparmakov</a><ul><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/104">Anton Altaparmakov</a></li><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/107">Anton Altaparmakov</a><ul><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/108">Anton Altaparmakov</a></li></ul></li><li class="origin"><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/137">Linus Torvalds</a><ul><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/137">Anton Altaparmakov</a><ul><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/142">Linus Torvalds</a></li></ul></li><li><a href="/lkml/2005/9/26/143">Al Viro</a></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerl.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="/" /></td><td class="c" rowspan="2" valign="top" style="padding-top: 1em"><table><tr><td colspan="2"><!--BuySellAds Zone Code--><div id="bsap_1297613" class="bsarocks bsap_5aa49c00cc06c882289a1dd6a5e50b62"></div><!--End BuySellAds Zone Code--></td></tr><tr><td><table><tr><td class="lp">Date</td><td class="rp" itemprop="datePublished">Mon, 26 Sep 2005 07:57:09 -0700 (PDT)</td></tr><tr><td class="lp">From</td><td class="rp" itemprop="author">Linus Torvalds &lt;&gt;</td></tr><tr><td class="lp">Subject</td><td class="rp" itemprop="name">Re: [PATCH 1/4] NTFS: Fix sparse warnings that have crept in over time.</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br /><br />On Mon, 26 Sep 2005, Anton Altaparmakov wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; NTFS: Fix sparse warnings that have crept in over time.<br /><br />I think this is wrong.<br /><br />What was the warning that caused this (and the two other things that look <br />the same)?<br /><br />&gt;  #define MK_MREF(m, s)	((MFT_REF)(((MFT_REF)(s) &lt;&lt; 48) |		\<br />&gt; -					((MFT_REF)(m) &amp; MFT_REF_MASK_CPU)))<br />&gt; +					((MFT_REF)(m) &amp; (u64)MFT_REF_MASK_CPU)))<br /><br />Also, side note: how you defined "MFT_REF_MASK_CPU" is pretty debatable in <br />the first place:<br /><br />	typedef enum {<br />	        MFT_REF_MASK_CPU        = 0x0000ffffffffffffULL,<br />	        MFT_REF_MASK_LE         = const_cpu_to_le64(0x0000ffffffffffffULL),<br />	} MFT_REF_CONSTS;<br /><br />and this just _happens_ to work with gcc, but it's not real C.<br /><br />The issue? "enum" is really an integer type. As in "int". Trying to put a <br />larger value than one that fits in "int" is not guaranteed to work.<br /><br />There's another issue, namely that the type of the snum is not only of <br />undefined size (is it the same size as an "int"? Is it an "unsigned long <br />long"?) but the "endianness" of it is also now totally undefined. You have <br />two different endiannesses inside the _same_ enum. What is the type of the <br />enum?<br /><br />You _really_ probably should use just<br /><br />	#define MFT_REF_MASK_CPU 0x0000ffffffffffffULL<br />	#define MFT_REF_MASK_LE const_cpu_to_le64(MFT_REF_MASK_CPU)<br /><br />instead. That way the type of that thing is well-defined.<br /><br />Depending on what warning you're trying to shut up, that may well fix it <br />too. Because now "MFT_REF_MASK_CPU" is clearly a regular constant, while <br />MFT_REF_MASK_LE is clearly a little-endian constant. Before, they were of <br />the same enum type, which made it very unclear what the hell they were.<br /><br />		Linus<br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.kernel.org<br />More majordomo info at  <a href="http://vger.kernel.org/majordomo-info.html">http://vger.kernel.org/majordomo-info.html</a><br />Please read the FAQ at  <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
